+\paragraph{Writhe and helicity upper-bound guard.}
+        \textbf{[ORTHODOX / NON-SHARP BOUNDS].}
+        For a smooth knot or link of length \(L\) carrying an embedded tube of
+        radius \(R\),
+        \begin{align}
+            |\operatorname{Wr}(K)|
+            <
+            \frac14\left(\frac{L}{R}\right)^{4/3}
+            =
+            \frac14\operatorname{Rop}_{\rm rad}(K)^{4/3}.
+            \label{eq:canon_writhe_ropelength_upper_bound}
+        \end{align}
+        For a smooth vector field \(\mathbf V\) on a bounded domain \(\Omega\),
+        the corresponding rough geometric helicity bound is
+        \begin{align}
+            |\mathscr H_V|
+            \leq
+            R_{\rm vol}(\Omega)\,\mathscr E_V,
+            \label{eq:canon_rough_helicity_volume_bound}
+        \end{align}
+        where \(R_{\rm vol}(\Omega)\) is the radius of a ball with the same volume
+        as \(\Omega\) and \(\mathscr E_V=\int_\Omega|\mathbf V|^2d^3x\)
+        \cite{CantarellaDeTurckGluck2001UpperBounds}.
+
+        \textbf{[CANON / PRECISION GUARD].}
+        Equations~\eqref{eq:canon_writhe_ropelength_upper_bound} and
+        \eqref{eq:canon_rough_helicity_volume_bound} are deliberately non-sharp.
+        They are admissibility and regression bounds, not estimators of particle
+        mass, chirality strength, or equilibrium helicity.  Sharp helicity bounds
+        require the domain-specific projected Biot--Savart/curl spectrum.
+
